				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Little Help on MANUAL Kiting<a name="56483"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 12 04 7:17 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>What I did was I went to the beach in Gunthank when no one was actively hunting there and I spent about 1 and a half hours practicing until I could pull it off without (or rarely)getting hit.... and using just run 3.  No selos even for the gathering stages.
<br />

<br />
There are several different tactics used and they just take practice.  Some run well formed circles, some turn before the song go's off, some run ovals and some run egg shapes.  
<br />

<br />
Once I have gathered said victims and got them into one many tenticaled monster I spiral into my circle making each rotation smaller and smaller.   I then get the consistant tapping down (I use right, clockwise circles).  On my taps I hold the key down slightly longer then I let it up.  I then begin singing my songs.  I've found for me that if by the time I've started and ended a song I've went through 270 degrees of my circle I have a good chance of landing the song, about 98% on my 35 range songs and 80-85% on my 30 range songs.  I also leave spell affects on... well because I have enough machine to push it and it helps with my song timing as you'll see.  So I imagine a clock on the floor.  I start my song at 12 o'clock and it lands when I'm at 9 o'clock and the mobs are at 6 o'clock.  I start my next song as soon as it lands and I get to 6 o'clock (right where my old spell effect is finishing fading) and the mobs are at 3 o'clock, then I land next song at 3 while mobs are at 12.  Once I get in the pattern I am able to focus very well and the mobs go down quick with the number of songs I'm landing.  Missed notes throw me off and my circle widens/distorts until I can get back into the pattern.  If I'm not landing my songs when I'm on the faded spell effect I hold down a little bit longer.  Finishing my song earlier then the effect often creates a corpse run for me.
<br />

<br />
I have also had some success with running a wider circle and giving one turn a bit tighter before the song lands.  On the 5 tics on the casting bar I tighten my turn up while the second to last tic of song is burning.  So, wide circle start song,
<br />
(this is casting bar, I know it burns down other way)
<br />
|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|
<br />
 normal  normal  normal  tight  normal
<br />
The Normal is just taps enough to maintain the wide circle.  The majority of the tight I'm pretty much holding the turn button down.  This strategy tends to make irregular circles and sometimes you drift and need to recenter yourself.
<br />

<br />
A few of the other things I've learned while manual kiting is that if the mobs stop following you graphically, they stop or vear off dramatically, that the best tactic is to run straight, no turns, or minimized turns until they finish the warp.  It saves me about a quarter to a third of the time.
<br />

<br />
The make up of a manual circle is much different than an auto circle.  With an auto circle your path is much wider than the path of the mobs that run a smaller circle inside yours.  With a manual circle the mobs run just a slightly smaller circle than your own.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, for what it's worth.  That's my experience with manual AOE.  I'm certain that I've far from perfected it and I'm sure there are other technics that can be learned.  Hope it helps.  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-2.gif" border="0" alt="Big Smile" hspace="2" /> </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
