			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Little Help on MANUAL Kiting<a name="57062"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 17 04 6:46 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>When you AE kite large numbers of mobs the server has a hard time synching mob location.  The jumpiness of mobs is not a function of your video card or system memory it's a matter of bandwidth and it's on the EQ serverside, not your isp.  When their server has to communicate the exact location of large numbers of mobs it will start to slow down somewhat, terrain and how closely mobs are stacked effects this quite a bit.
<br />

<br />
I came to this conclusion gather groups up for AE kiting.  What I found was that the further the mobs were strung out the more erratically they behaved.... I actually see the packet received % spike when this happens, I've tested it enough that I know it's not my isp or just coincidence.  The tighter you keep your mobs the less trouble the server has sending the correct mob location to your machine.  Auto circling ensures the tightest mob formation.. actually any kind of tight circle makes for tight mob formation, the tighter your mobs are packed the less erratic their behavoiur will appear and the less likely you'll be to get hit.
<br />

<br />
The key to manual kiting is running in whatever pattern you're most comfortable with, that keeps your mobs packed tight.  The exact size and shape of your kite area will detirmine what sort of timeing you need to encorporate in your twisting.  Auto circling or doing perfect circles doesn't really require much in the way of timing, the more eccentric your kite pattern the more demanding your timing becomes.
<br />

<br />
Practice.  In the end, as with every other bard ability, practice makes perfect.  Try AE kiting in a variety of places, Dulak's is nice for the loot and lots of smooth terrain but sometimes rougher terrain can work to your advantage, keeping mobs packed closer to gether.  Different zones and different mobs reauire different run speeds as well, again, only trial and error will really teach you anything here.
<br />

<br />
I died ALOT when I first started AE kiting, and then I thought I had it mastered and moved on to another zone to try it and found that I had to relearn the entire process, new zone, new mobs, new requirements for AE kiting, lots more deaths while learning.  AE kiting is risky and rewarding.  I went from an AA about once every hour soloing to 3 or more an hour depending on how ambitious I'm feeling... and yes, I still die from time to time.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><img src="http://www.geetronics.com/liis4.jpg"><hr>
Liis Tenning, Impresario Vah Shir Maestro, Drinal Server - Malevolent Spirits</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
